ps]] || [[Amber Neben]] || [[Tina Pic]]\n|-\n| 2004 || [[Kristin Armstrong]] || [[Christine Thorburn]] || [[Tina Pic]]\n|-\n| 2005 || [[Katheryn Curi Mattis]] || [[Lynn Gaggioli]] || [[Tina Pic]]\n|-\n| 2006 || [[Kristin Armstrong]] || [[Christine Thorburn]] || [[Amber Neben]]\n|-\n| 2007 || [[Mara Abbott]] || [[Kristin Armstrong]] || [[Amber Neben]]\n|-\n| 2008 || [[Brooke Miller]] || [[Tina Pic]] || [[Katharine Carroll]]\n|-\n| 2009 || [[Meredith Miller]] || [[Chrissy Ruiter]] || [[Kristin LaSasso]]\n|-\n| 2010 || [[Mara Abbott]] || [[Shelley Evans]] || [[Carmen Small]]\n|-\n| 2011 || [[Robin Farina]] || [[Andrea Dvorak]] || [[Amanda Miller (cyclist)|Amanda Miller]]\n|-\n| 2012 || [[Megan Guarnier]] || [[Lauren Hall]] || [[Carmen Small]]\n|-\n| 2013 || [[Jade Wilcoxson]] || [[Lauren Hall]] || [[Alison Powers]]\n|-\n| 2014 || [[Alison Powers]] || [[Megan Guarnier]] || [[Evelyn Stevens]]\n|-\n| 2015 || [[Megan Guarnier]] || [[Coryn Rivera]] || [[Tayler Wiles]]\n|-\n| 2016<ref>{{cite news|title=2016 USA CYCLING PRO ROAD RACE & TT NATIONALS|url=https://www.usacycling.org/results/index.php?permit=2016-24|accessdate=29 June 2017|work=USA Cycling|date=28 May 2016}}</ref> || [[Megan Guarnier]] || [[Coryn Rivera]] || [[Mandy Heintz]]\n|-\n| 2017<ref>{{cite news|title=NEBEN, WARBASSE CROWNED ROAD RACE NATIONAL CHAMPIONS|url=http://www.usacycling.org/neben-warbasse-crowned-road-race-national-champions.htm|accessdate=29 June 2017|work=USA Cycling|date=26 June 2017}}</ref> || [[Amber Neben]] || [[Coryn Rivera]] || [[Ruth Winder]]\n|-\n| 2018<ref>{{cite news|title=Rivera wins stars-and-stripes jersey at US Pro Road Championships|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/usa-cycling-pro-road-itt-and-criterium-national-championships-2018/elite-women-road-race/results/|accessdate=3 August 2018|work=USA Cycling|date=24 June 2018}}</ref> || [[Coryn Rivera]] || [[Megan Guarnier]] || [[Emma White (cyclist)|Emma White]]\n|-\n| 2019<ref>{{cite news|title=USA Cycling Pro Road Championships 2019: Elite Women Road Race Results|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/usa-cycling-pro-road-championships-2019/elite-women-road-race/results}}</ref> || [[Ruth Winder]] || [[Coryn Rivera]] || [[Emma White (cyclist)|Emma White]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[United States National Criterium Championships]]\n*[[United States National Time Trial Championships]]\n*[[United States National Road Race Championships (historical)]] 1921-1964\n\n==Notes==\n {{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.usacycling.org USA Cycling]\n* [http://www.usacycling.org/news/user/story.php?id=320 USA Cycling National Champions]\n* [http://www.procyclingtour.com/history.cfm Pro Cycling Tour]\n* [http://www.cyclingwebsite.net/wedstrijdfiche.php?wedstrijdid=6301 Women's results at cyclingwebsite.net]\n\n{{National Road Race Championships}}\n\n[[Category:National road cycling championships]]\n[[Category:Cycle races in the United States]]\n[[Category:Recurring events with year of establishment missing]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:MaillotUSA.PNG|thumb|right|200px|The champions jersey]]\n[[File:George Hincapie 2010 TOC.jpg|thumb|right|165px|George Hincapie.]]\nThe '''United States National Professional Road Race Championships''' began in 1985. They are run by the governing body, [[USA Cycling]]. Until 2006 the race was open to all nationalities, the first American to finish being named the winner and given a distinctive jersey. Since the championship in [[Greenville, South Carolina]], in 2006, all riders have had to be American.\n\nBefore 1985, only the amateur champions were named.\nFrom 1921 to 1964, the Amateur Bicycle League of America [[United States National Road Race Championships#See also|(ABLA) National Championships]] were held as an omnium of track-style events for Men, Women, and Juniors, rather than as a road race. In 1964 the American Cycling Newsletter (later [[Bicycling (magazine)|Bicycling]]) reported the results of a Flemington, NJ race as the national road racing championships, but these results do not appear in the [[USA Cycling]] list of winners.\n\n==Men==\n\n===Amateur===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width: 60%; text-align:left;\"\n|-\n|style=\"background:#DDDDDD; font-weight:bold; text-align:center;\"| Year \n|style=\"background:gold;font-weight:bold; text-align:center;\" | Gold \n|style=\"background:silver; font-weight:bold; text-align:center;\" | Silver \n|style=\"background:#cc9966; font-weight:bold; text-align:center;\" | Bronze\n|-\n|-\n|1964<ref>{{cite journal |title=National 100 kilometer Road Championships |journal=American Cycling Newsletter |date=Oct 1964 |volume=3 |issue=8 |page=29 |format=print }}</ref> \n|| [[Bob Parsons (cyclist)|Bob Parsons]] ||Bill Ennis || Harry Morton\n|-\n|1965<ref>{{cite news |format=print |title=Hiltner wins road: Tops nation's best after 10,000 feet of climbing |work=American Cycling |location=Oakland, Ca |publisher=American Cycling Press |date=October 1965|pages=30\u201334 }}</ref> \n|| [[Michael Hiltner]] || Stuart Baillie || [[John Allis]]\n|-\n|1966 || [[Bob Tetzlaff]] ||  || \n|-\n|1967 || [[Bob Parsons (cyclist)|Bob Parsons]] || [[Daniel Butler (cyclist)|Daniel Butler]] || [[John Aschen]] \n|-\n|1968 || [[John Howard (cyclist)|John Howard]] || ||\n|-\n|1969 || [[Alan DeFever]] ||  || \n|-\n|1970<ref>{{cite news | title = Rochester Research Chemist Wills Bike Racing Title Here | date = 22 Aug 1970 | url = http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F6081EFF3E5B137A93C0AB1783D85F448785F9 | work = The New York Times | accessdate = 2012-11-17}}</ref> || [[Mike Carnahan]] || [[Mike Levonas]] || [[Doug Dale (cyclist)|Doug Dale]] \n|-\n|1971 || [[Steve Dayton (cyclist)|Steve Dayton]] ||  || \n|-\n|1972 || [[John Howard (cyclist)|John Howard]] || [[Wayne Stetina]] || [[Bob Schneider (cyclist)|Bob Schneider]]\n|-\n|1973 || [[John Howard (cyclist)|John Howard]] ||[[Bob Schneider (cyclist)|Bob Schneider]]  || [[Rick Ball (cyclist)|Rick Ball]]\n|-\n|1974 || [[John Allis]] || [[Thomas Officer]] ||