{"title_page": "Inge Thun", "text_new": "{{short description|Norwegian footballer and bandy player}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name          = Inge Thun\n| image               =\n| fullname            = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1945|6|17|df=yes}}\n| birth_place         = [[Drammen]], [[Norway]]\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2008|2|15|1945|6|17|df=yes}}\n| death_place         = [[Drammen]], [[Norway]]\n| clubnumber          = \n| position            = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = [[Str\u00f8msgodset IF]]\n| years1 = 1963\u20131977\n| clubs1 = [[Str\u00f8msgodset IF]]\n| caps1 = 329   \n| goals1 = 0 \n| nationalyears1 = 1968\u20131974\n| nationalteam1 = [[Norway national football team|Norway]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 4  \n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n}}\n\n'''Inge Thun''' (17 June 1945 \u2212 15 February 2008) was a [[Norway|Norwegian]] [[association football|football]] goalkeeper and [[bandy]] winger who played for [[Str\u00f8msgodset IF]] in both sports. He finished his football career with a few seasons across the river at [[Drammens Ballklubb]].\n\nHe won the [[Norwegian Premier League|Norwegian football league]] with Str\u00f8msgodset in 1970 as well the [[Norwegian Football Cup|Cup]] in 1969, 1970 and 1973. He also became Norwegian bandy champion six times with Str\u00f8msgodset and won a silver medal in the [[1965 Bandy World Championship|1965]] [[Bandy World Championship]] with the [[Norway national bandy team|national team]].\n\nThun became famous in England when his team lost 0-11 to Liverpool in the 1975 [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|Cup Winners' Cup]].\n\nInge Thun died on 15 February 2008, after suffering a [[stroke]].\n\n==External links==\n*[https://archive.is/20110717095926/http://dt.no/article/20080215/NYHET/806245535/1004/NYHET Obituary], ''[[Drammens Tidende]]'' {{in lang|no}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thun, Inge}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n[[Category:Norwegian footballers]]\n[[Category:Norway international footballers]]\n[[Category:Str\u00f8msgodset Toppfotball players]]\n[[Category:Norwegian bandy players]]\n\n\n{{Norway-footy-goalkeeper-stub}}\n{{Bandy-bio-stub}}\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name          = Inge Thun\n| image               =\n| fullname            = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1945|6|17|df=yes}}\n| birth_place         = [[Drammen]], [[Norway]]\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2008|2|15|1945|6|17|df=yes}}\n| death_place         = [[Drammen]], [[Norway]]\n| clubnumber          = \n| position            = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = [[Str\u00f8msgodset IF]]\n| years1 = 1963\u20131977\n| clubs1 = [[Str\u00f8msgodset IF]]\n| caps1 = 329   \n| goals1 = 0 \n| nationalyears1 = 1968\u20131974\n| nationalteam1 = [[Norway national football team|Norway]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 4  \n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n}}\n\n'''Inge Thun''' (17 June 1945 \u2212 15 February 2008) was a [[Norway|Norwegian]] [[association football|football]] goalkeeper and [[bandy]] winger who played for [[Str\u00f8msgodset IF]] in both sports. He finished his football career with a few seasons across the river at [[Drammens Ballklubb]].\n\nHe won the [[Norwegian Premier League|Norwegian football league]] with Str\u00f8msgodset in 1970 as well the [[Norwegian Football Cup|Cup]] in 1969, 1970 and 1973. He also became Norwegian bandy champion six times with Str\u00f8msgodset and won a silver medal in the [[1965 Bandy World Championship|1965]] [[Bandy World Championship]] with the [[Norway national bandy team|national team]].\n\nThun became famous in England when his team lost 0-11 to Liverpool in the 1975 [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|Cup Winners' Cup]].\n\nInge Thun died on 15 February 2008, after suffering a [[stroke]].\n\n==External links==\n*[https://archive.is/20110717095926/http://dt.no/article/20080215/NYHET/806245535/1004/NYHET Obituary], ''[[Drammens Tidende]]'' {{in lang|no}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thun, Inge}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n[[Category:Norwegian footballers]]\n[[Category:Norway international footballers]]\n[[Category:Str\u00f8msgodset Toppfotball players]]\n[[Category:Norwegian bandy players]]\n\n\n{{Norway-footy-goalkeeper-stub}}\n{{Bandy-bio-stub}}\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"Norwegian footballer and bandy player\", overriding Wikidata description \"Norwegian footballer\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inge_Thun"}
{"title_page": "Vrsinje", "text_new": "'''Vrsinje''' ({{lang-sh|\u0412\u0440\u0441\u0438\u045a\u0435}}, {{lang-la|Versigne, Versigna}}) was a medieval county (''[[\u017eupa]]'') part of the [[Kingdom of Serbia (medieval)|Kingdom of Serbia]], the [[Kingdom of Bosnia]], and briefly, as a ''[[Nahiye (Ottoman)|nahiya]]'' of the [[Ottoman Empire]]. It was a county in the land of ''[[Travunija]]''. After the Ottoman conquest, it was replaced by the [[Zupci]].\n\n==Geography, economy and culture==\nVrsinje was located on the way from [[Trebinje]] (now in Bosnia and Herzegovina) to [[Herceg Novi]] (now in Montenegro), above [[Konavle]] (now in Croatia).{{sfn|Jire\u010dek|1951|p=42}} It bordered the counties of [[Trebinje (\u017eupa)|Trebinje]],<ref name=\"Popov2000\">{{cite book|author=\u010cedomir Popov|title=Istorija srpske dr\u017eavnosti|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kg01AAAAMAAJ|year=2000|publisher=Srpska akademija nauka i umetnosti|page=33|quote=<!--\u0408\u0435\u0437\u0433\u0440\u043e \u0436\u0443\u043f\u0435 \u0422\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0438\u045a\u0435 \u0447\u0438\u043d\u0438\u043b\u043e \u0458\u0435 \u0422\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0438\u045a\u0441\u043a\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0459\u0435, \u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0458\u0435 \u043e\u043d\u043e \u0431\u0438\u043b\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0437\u0430\u043d\u043e \u0441\u0430 \u0441\u0443\u0441\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0438\u043c \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043e\u043d\u0438\u043c \u0446\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043c\u0430, \u043a\u0430\u043e \u0448\u0442\u043e \u0441\u0443: \u0428\u0443\u043c\u0430, \u041f\u043e\u0432\u0440\u0448, \u0412\u0440\u0441\u0438\u045a\u0435 \u0438 \u041b\u0443\u0433.-->}}</ref> [[Vrm (\u017eupa)|Vrm]],<ref>{{cite book|title=Bulletin du Mus\u00e9e etnographique de C\u00e9tign\u00e9|volume=4|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GCDQAAAAMAAJ|year=1964|publisher=Muzej|page=110|quote=<!--\u0418\u0437 \u0441\u0432\u0435\u0433\u0430 \u0448\u0442\u043e \u0437\u043d\u0430\u043c\u043e \u043e \u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0430\u0458\u0443 \u0442\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0443\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0436\u0443\u043f\u0430 \u0441\u0440\u0435\u0434\u045a\u0435\u0433 \u0432\u0435\u043a\u0430, \u043f\u043e\u0443\u0437\u0434\u0430\u043d\u043e \u0441\u0435 \u043c\u043e\u0436\u0435 \u0440\u0435\u045b\u0438 \u0434\u0430 \u0441\u0443 \u0441\u0435 \u0442\u0440\u0438 \u043e\u0434 \u045a\u0438\u0445 \u043d\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0437\u0438\u043b\u0435 \u043e\u043a\u043e \u0436\u0443\u043f\u0435 \u0412\u0440\u043c\u0430 \u0438 \u0434\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0440\u0438\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0435 \u0441 \u045a\u043e\u043c. \u0422\u043e \u0441\u0443 \u0436\u0443\u043f\u0430 \u0422\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0438\u045a\u0430 \u0438 \u0436\u0443\u043f\u0435 \u0420\u0443\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0435 \u0438 \u0412\u0440\u0441\u0438\u045a\u0435. -->}}</ref> Konavle and [[Dra\u010devica (\u017eupa)|Dra\u010devica]]. It included the settlement of Mrcine (which Jire\u010dek identified as Vrsinje itself, known as Mrcine since the 16th century),{{sfn|Jire\u010dek|1951|p=42}} now known as Dubravka, in Konavle. Jire\u010dek's identification of Mrcine as Vrsinje itself was proved false, as Mrcine was mentioned already in 1423 and 1427 in boundary settlements of Konavle lands.{{sfn|SKA|1925|p=39}} A larger size of Vrsinje is apparent from its often mention alongside Trebinje and Konavle.{{sfn|SKA|1925|pp=3\u20134}}\n\nAccording to Jire\u010dek, there were dense forests around Vrsinje (now without traces) from which planks were sold in Ragusa ([[Dubrovnik]]), Konavle and the [[Bay of Kotor]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Glasnik Hrvatskog dr\u017eavnog muzeja u Sarajevu|volume=55|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SXvRAAAAMAAJ|year=1944|publisher=Dr\u017eavna tiskara|quote=<!--Jiri\u010dek veli, da su se iz velikih \u0161uma oko Vrsinja (kraj Trebinja), gdje vi\u0161e nema ni traga od \u0161ume, izvozile daske u Dubrovnik, Konavle i Kotorski zaljev.-->}}</ref> From Vrsinje and Konavle meat, especially salted pork ([[prosciutto]]), leather, horns, wool and cheese was exported to Ragusa.{{sfn|Jire\u010dek|1951|p=42}} In 1310, two individuals from Vrsinje migrated to the [[Republic of Ragusa]] to work as servants.<ref>{{cite book|title=\u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0458\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0447\u0430\u0441\u043e\u043f\u0438\u0441 31 (1984): Historical Review 31 (1984)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HMhqCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA45|date=1 August 1984|publisher=Istorijski institut|pages=45\u2013|id=GGKEY:5LA3DP5RFU7}}</ref>\n\nVrsinje was inhabited by warlike shepherds.{{sfn|Jire\u010dek|1951|p=42}} The Dobra\u0161inovi\u0107 was a lesser noble family from Vrsinje, mentioned in the first half of the 15th century; Vukosav Dobra\u0161inovi\u0107 was mentioned between 1426 and 1433 several times in Ragusan documents, while Toma\u0161 Dobra\u0161inovi\u0107 was mentioned in 1439.{{sfn|Rudi\u0107|2006|p=107}} Names of people from Vrsinje are recorded in documents; examples include 14th-century Rajko Milatkovi\u0107{{sfn|Peco|1987|p=163}} or Milatovi\u0107 (1376),{{sfn|Vego|1957|p=138}} and 15th-century Radut Radosali\u0107 (1416),{{sfn|Kurtovi\u0107|2009|p=60}} Vukosav Dobra\u0161inovi\u0107 (1426\u201333),{{sfn|Rudi\u0107|2006|p=107}} Vukman Bogav\u010di\u0107 (1426),{{sfn|Kurtovi\u0107|2009|p=23}} Pribio Bogav\u010di\u0107 (1429),{{sfn|Kurtovi\u0107|2009|p=23}} Petko Radosali\u0107 (1432),{{sfn|Kurtovi\u0107|2009|p=78}} Radonja Paska\u010devi\u0107 (1434),<ref>{{cite book|title=Acta historico-oeconomica Iugoslaviae|volume=14\u201316|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9s3sAAAAMAAJ|year=1987|publisher=Komisija za Ekonomsku Historiju Jugoslavije|page=52}}</ref> Radohna and Ostoja Radosali\u0107 (1438),{{sfn|Kurtovi\u0107|2009|p=78}} \"Vatoyl\" and \"Butor Cranchouigh\" (1438),{{sfn|Kurtovi\u0107|2009|p=78}} Toma\u0161 Dobra\u0161inovi\u0107 (1439),{{sfn|Rudi\u0107|2006|p=107}} Dobrovoj Branojevi\u0107,{{sfn|Peco|1987|p=159}} Branko Dobrovojevi\u0107,{{sfn|Peco|1987|p=159}} Hranko Jirojevi\u0107,{{sfn|Peco|1987|p=160}} Vukac Milatovi\u0107,{{sfn|Peco|1987|p=168}} Rogu\u0161in Milo\u0161evi\u0107,{{sfn|Peco|1987|p=168}} Vuk\u0161a Pribilovi\u0107,{{sfn|Peco|1987|p=168}} Boroje,{{sfn|Peco|1987|p=168}} Branko Dobrojevi\u0107,{{sfn|Peco|1987|p=168}} and Dobroslav Stanojevi\u0107.{{sfn|Vego|1957|p=138}} Bosnian linguist Asim Peco noted that almost all names of individuals from Vrsinje were Serb.{{sfn|Peco|1987|p=168}}\n\n==History==\nVrsinje was an old county of the province of [[Travunija]].{{sfn|SKA|1925|p=3}}){{sfn|Duni\u0107|1967|p=76}} It was located in the eastern part of its territory.{{sfn|Vego|1957|p=72}} It was held by the medieval Serbian state until the late 14th century. It was held by magnates [[Nikola Altomanovi\u0107]] until 1373, then [[\u0110ura\u0111 I Bal\u0161i\u0107]] until 1377, after which it was taken by [[Tvrtko I of Bosnia]], during the [[Fall of the Serbian Empire]].\n\nBosnian magnate [[Sandalj Hrani\u0107]] received southern Konavle and its city Sokol in 1392,{{sfn|Vego|1957|p=72}} and also held Vrsinje (as mentioned in 1424).<ref name=\"umetnosti1940\">{{cite book|author=Srpska akademija nauka i umetnosti|title=Glas|issue=182|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zt8rAQAAIAAJ|year=1940|publisher=U Kralj.-srpskoj dr\u017eavnoj \u0161tampariji|page=165|quote=<!--\u0412\u0440\u0441\u0438\u045a\u0435 \u0458\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u043f\u0430\u0434\u0430\u043b\u043e \u0421\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0430\u0459\u0443-->}}</ref> In the 1440s, there were frequent flights from Trebinje, Vrsinje and Dra\u010devica into Ragusan territory.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Niko Kapetani\u0107|author2=Nenad Vekari\u0107|title=Stanovni\u0161tvo Konavala|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HN3kAAAAIAAJ|date=1 January 1999|publisher=Zavod za povijesne znanosti HAZU|page=98}}</ref> After Bosnian king [[Thomas of Bosnia|Stephen Thomas]] and the Serbian despot reconciled,{{when|date=May 2016}} the [[Republic of Ragusa]] proposed a league against the \"Duke of St. Sava\", [[Stjepan Vuk\u010di\u0107 Kosa\u010da]].{{sfn|Bo\u017ei\u0107|1952|p=119}} In 1451, King Stephen Thomas ceded over the counties of Vrsinje and [[Dra\u010devica (\u017eupa)|Dra\u010devica]] to Ragusa.{{sfn|\u0106irkovi\u0107|Mihalj\u010di\u0107|1999|p=32}} The Ragusans were allowed to raise castles in the ceded territory.{{sfn|\u0106irkovi\u0107|Mihalj\u010di\u0107|1999|p=32}} Thomas' charter from 18 December 1451 also included the obligation that he would attack Stjepan Vuk\u010di\u0107 Kosa\u010da, but the ceding was only theoretical, as Duke Stjepan firmly held those territories.{{sfn|Bo\u017ei\u0107|1952|p=120}}\n\nDuring the period of the [[Duchy of St. Sava]], Vrsinje changed hands several times from the Duchy to the Ottomans, and from the Ottomans back to the Duchy.{{sfn|Atanasovski|1979|p=117}} Vrsinje was held by the Ottomans already in September 1465.{{sfn|Atanasovski|1979|p=117}} Ottoman ''[[suba\u015fi]]'' are present in Vrsinje on 17 April and 20 August 1466, while [[Vlachs (social class)|Vlachs shepherd community]] of Zupci, as ''jurisdictio Turcorum'', are present there on 7 October 1466.{{sfn|Atanasovski|1979|p=117}} As seen from the Ottoman ''[[defter]]'' of 1475\u201377, the Zupci ''nahija'' replaced Vrsinje.{{sfn|Atanasovski|1979|p=118}} The Zupci had earlier been mentioned as a family or people part of Vrsinje; in 1403 as \"homo de Versigna Xube\u00e7\", in 1421 as \"de Versigne de genere Zuba\u00e7\", in 1466 as \"de Versigne Vlachos Xubci sic dictos\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Archiv f\u00fcr slavische Philologie|volume=19|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J1fRAAAAMAAJ|year=1897|publisher=Europa Printing|page=26}}</ref> The tribe of Zupci replaced the name of Vrsinje.{{sfn|Duni\u0107|1967|p=76}} On 28 January 1501, a new ''vojvoda'' of Novi, Vrsinje and Trebinje is mentioned;<ref name=\"Hercegovine1955\">{{cite book|author=Istorisko dru\u0161tvo Bosne i Hercegovine|volume=7|title=Godi\u0161njak|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6k0iAAAAMAAJ|year=1955|pages=57, 64}}</ref> this is the last time Vrsinje is mentioned as an administrative unit.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Atanasovski|first=Veljan|title=Pad Hercegovine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j4whAAAAMAAJ|year=1979|publisher=Istorijski Institut|pages=13, 47, 71, 117, 118|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bo\u017ei\u0107|first=Ivan|title=\u0414\u0443\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0438\u043a \u0438 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0443 XIV \u0438 XV \u0432\u0435\u043a\u0443|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7n1TAAAAYAAJ|year=1952|publisher=\u041d\u0430\u0443\u0447\u043d\u0430 \u043a\u045a\u0438\u0433\u0430|pages=119, 120, 190, 207|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=\u0106irkovi\u0107|first1=Sima|authorlink1=Sima \u0106irkovi\u0107|last2=Mihalj\u010di\u0107|first2=Rade|authorlink2=Rade Mihalj\u010di\u0107|script-title=sr:\u041b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043d \u0441\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433 \u0441\u0440\u0435\u0434\u045a\u0435\u0433 \u0432\u0435\u043a\u0430|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AypYAAAAMAAJ|year=1999|publisher=Knowledge|ref=harv|language=sr}}\n* {{cite book|last=Duni\u0107|first=Mihailo|title=Les Familles nobles de Hum et de Trebinje ...|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6Y8OAQAAIAAJ|year=1967|publisher=Acad\u00e9mie serbe des sciences et des arts|pages=53, 76, 77|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Jire\u010dek|first=Josif Konstantin|title=Trgova\u010dki drumovi i rudnici Srbije i Bosne u srednjem vijeku|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BB89AAAAMAAJ|year=1951|publisher=Svjetlost|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Kurtovi\u0107|first=Esad|title=\u0420\u0430\u0434\u043e\u0441\u0430\u043b\u0438\u045b\u0438 - \u043f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u0458\u0435\u0440 \"\u0458\u0435\u0434\u043d\u043e\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0430\" \u0441\u0440\u0435\u0434\u045a\u0435\u0433\u0430 \u0432\u0438\u0458\u0435\u043a\u0430|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MSsqCwAAQBAJ|year=2009|publisher=Istorijski institut Beograd|pages=23 |id=GGKEY:WUKYQDYP46L|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Peco|first=Asim|title=Iz jezi\u010dke teorije i prakse|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lc0cAAAAMAAJ|year=1987|publisher=Nau\u010dna knj.|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Rudi\u0107|first=Srdjan|title=\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0430 \u0418\u043b\u0438\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433 \u0433\u0440\u0431\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430: The Nobility of the Illyric Coat of Arms|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FHB6BwAAQBAJ&pg=PA107|year=2006|publisher=Istorijski institut Beograd|isbn=978-86-7743-055-9|page=107|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|author=SKA|title=Spomenik Srpske kraljevske akademije|volume=62\u201367|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Dl-1qjyPwxUC|year=1925|publisher=U Dr\u017eavnoj \u0161tampariji Kraljevne Srbije|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Vego|first=Marko|title=Naselja bosanske srednjevjekovne dr\u017eave|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yoPRAAAAMAAJ|year=1957|publisher=Svjetlost|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Dobra\u0161inovi\u0107i iz Vrsinja (Datiranje natpisa na ste\u0107ku Vuka\u0161ina Dobra\u0161inovi\u0107a iz Konjskog kod Trebinja), Godi\u0161njak CBI 39, Sarajevo 2010, 163\u2013171.\n\n{{coord|42.6400204|18.3921432|region:BA_type:adm2nd|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vrsinje}}\n[[Category:Medieval Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Historical regions of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n", "text_old": "'''Vrsinje''' ({{lang-sh|\u0412\u0440\u0441\u0438\u045a\u0435}}, {{lang-la|Versigne, Versigna}}) was a medieval county (''[[\u017eupa]]'') part of the [[Kingdom of Serbia (medieval)|Kingdom of Serbia]], the [[Kingdom of Bosnia]], and briefly, as a ''[[Nahiye (Ottoman)|nahiya]]'' of the [[Ottoman Empire]]. It was a county in the land of ''[[Travunija]]''. After the Ottoman conquest, it was replaced by the [[Zupci]].\n\n==Geography, economy and culture==\nVrsinje was located on the way from [[Trebinje]] (now in Bosnia and Herzegovina) to [[Herceg Novi]] (now in Montenegro), above [[Konavle]] (now in Croatia).{{sfn|Jire\u010dek|1951|p=42}} It bordered the counties of [[Trebinje (\u017eupa)|Trebinje]],<ref name=\"Popov2000\">{{cite book|author=\u010cedomir Popov|title=Istorija srpske dr\u017eavnosti|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kg01AAAAMAAJ|year=2000|publisher=Srpska akademija nauka i umetnosti|page=33|quote=<!--\u0408\u0435\u0437\u0433\u0440\u043e \u0436\u0443\u043f\u0435 \u0422\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0438\u045a\u0435 \u0447\u0438\u043d\u0438\u043b\u043e \u0458\u0435 \u0422\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0438\u045a\u0441\u043a\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0459\u0435, \u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0458\u0435 \u043e\u043d\u043e \u0431\u0438\u043b\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0437\u0430\u043d\u043e \u0441\u0430 \u0441\u0443\u0441\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0438\u043c \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043e\u043d\u0438\u043c \u0446\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043c\u0430, \u043a\u0430\u043e \u0448\u0442\u043e \u0441\u0443: \u0428\u0443\u043c\u0430, \u041f\u043e\u0432\u0440\u0448, \u0412\u0440\u0441\u0438\u045a\u0435 \u0438 \u041b\u0443\u0433.-->}}</ref> [[Vrm (\u017eupa)|Vrm]],<ref>{{cite book|title=Bulletin du Mus\u00e9e etnographique de C\u00e9tign\u00e9|volume=4|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GCDQAAAAMAAJ|year=1964|publisher=Muzej|page=110|quote=<!--\u0418\u0437 \u0441\u0432\u0435\u0433\u0430 \u0448\u0442\u043e \u0437\u043d\u0430\u043c\u043e \u043e \u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0430\u0458\u0443 \u0442\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0443\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0436\u0443\u043f\u0430 \u0441\u0440\u0435\u0434\u045a\u0435\u0433 \u0432\u0435\u043a\u0430, \u043f\u043e\u0443\u0437\u0434\u0430\u043d\u043e \u0441\u0435 \u043c\u043e\u0436\u0435 \u0440\u0435\u045b\u0438 \u0434\u0430 \u0441\u0443 \u0441\u0435 \u0442\u0440\u0438 \u043e\u0434 \u045a\u0438\u0445 \u043d\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0437\u0438\u043b\u0435 \u043e\u043a\u043e \u0436\u0443\u043f\u0435 \u0412\u0440\u043c\u0430 \u0438 \u0434\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0440\u0438\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0435 \u0441 \u045a\u043e\u043c. \u0422\u043e \u0441\u0443 \u0436\u0443\u043f\u0430 \u0422\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0438\u045a\u0430 \u0438 \u0436\u0443\u043f\u0435 \u0420\u0443\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0435 \u0438 \u0412\u0440\u0441\u0438\u045a\u0435. -->}}</ref> Konavle and [[Dra\u010devica (\u017eupa)|Dra\u010devica]]. It included the settlement of Mrcine (which Jire\u010dek identified as Vrsinje itself, known as Mrcine since the 16th century),{{sfn|Jire\u010dek|1951|p=42}} now known as Dubravka, in Konavle. Jire\u010dek's identification of Mrcine as Vrsinje itself was proved false, as Mrcine was mentioned already in 1423 and 1427 in boundary settlements of Konavle lands.{{sfn|SKA|1925|p=39}} A larger size of Vrsinje is apparent from its often mention alongside Trebinje and Konavle.{{sfn|SKA|1925|pp=3\u20134}}\n\nAccording to Jire\u010dek, there were dense forests around Vrsinje (now without traces) from which planks were sold in Ragusa ([[Dubrovnik]]), Konavle and the [[Bay of Kotor]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Glasnik Hrvatskog dr\u017eavnog muzeja u Sarajevu|volume=55|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SXvRAAAAMAAJ|year=1944|publisher=Dr\u017eavna tiskara|quote=<!--Jiri\u010dek veli, da su se iz velikih \u0161uma oko Vrsinja (kraj Trebinja), gdje vi\u0161e nema ni traga od \u0161ume, izvozile daske u Dubrovnik, Konavle i Kotorski zaljev.-->}}</ref> From Vrsinje and Konavle meat, especially salted pork ([[prosciutto]]), leather, horns, wool and cheese was exported to Ragusa.{{sfn|Jire\u010dek|1951|p=42}} In 1310, two individuals from Vrsinje migrated to the [[Republic of Ragusa]] to work as servants.<ref>{{cite book|title=\u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0458\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0447\u0430\u0441\u043e\u043f\u0438\u0441 31 (1984): Historical Review 31 (1984)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HMhqCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA45|date=1 August 1984|publisher=Istorijski institut|pages=45\u2013|id=GGKEY:5LA3DP5RFU7}}</ref>\n\nVrsinje was inhabited by warlike shepherds.{{sfn|Jire\u010dek|1951|p=42}} The Dobra\u0161inovi\u0107 was a lesser noble family from Vrsinje, mentioned in the first half of the 15th century; Vukosav Dobra\u0161inovi\u0107 was mentioned between 1426 and 1433 several times in Ragusan documents, while Toma\u0161 Dobra\u0161inovi\u0107 was mentioned in 1439.{{sfn|Rudi\u0107|2006|p=107}} Names of people from Vrsinje are recorded in documents; examples include 14th-century Rajko Milatkovi\u0107{{sfn|Peco|1987|p=163}} or Milatovi\u0107 (1376),{{sfn|Vego|1957|p=138}} and 15th-century Radut Radosali\u0107 (1416),{{sfn|Kurtovi\u0107|2009|p=60}} Vukosav Dobra\u0161inovi\u0107 (1426\u201333),{{sfn|Rudi\u0107|2006|p=107}} Vukman Bogav\u010di\u0107 (1426),{{sfn|Kurtovi\u0107|2009|p=23}} Pribio Bogav\u010di\u0107 (1429),{{sfn|Kurtovi\u0107|2009|p=23}} Petko Radosali\u0107 (1432),{{sfn|Kurtovi\u0107|2009|p=78}} Radonja Paska\u010devi\u0107 (1434),<ref>{{cite book|title=Acta historico-oeconomica Iugoslaviae|volume=14\u201316|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9s3sAAAAMAAJ|year=1987|publisher=Komisija za Ekonomsku Historiju Jugoslavije|page=52}}</ref> Radohna and Ostoja Radosali\u0107 (1438),{{sfn|Kurtovi\u0107|2009|p=78}} \"Vatoyl\" and \"Butor Cranchouigh\" (1438),{{sfn|Kurtovi\u0107|2009|p=78}} Toma\u0161 Dobra\u0161inovi\u0107 (1439),{{sfn|Rudi\u0107|2006|p=107}} Dobrovoj Branojevi\u0107,{{sfn|Peco|1987|p=159}} Branko Dobrovojevi\u0107,{{sfn|Peco|1987|p=159}} Hranko Jirojevi\u0107,{{sfn|Peco|1987|p=160}} Vukac Milatovi\u0107,{{sfn|Peco|1987|p=168}} Rogu\u0161in Milo\u0161evi\u0107,{{sfn|Peco|1987|p=168}} Vuk\u0161a Pribilovi\u0107,{{sfn|Peco|1987|p=168}} Boroje,{{sfn|Peco|1987|p=168}} Branko Dobrojevi\u0107,{{sfn|Peco|1987|p=168}} and Dobroslav Stanojevi\u0107.{{sfn|Vego|1957|p=138}} Bosnian linguist Asim Peco noted that almost all names of individuals from Vrsinje were Serb.{{sfn|Peco|1987|p=168}}\n\n==History==\nVrsinje was an old county of the province of [[Travunija]].{{sfn|SKA|1925|p=3}}){{sfn|Duni\u0107|1967|p=76}} It was located in the eastern part of its territory.{{sfn|Vego|1957|p=72}} It was held by the medieval Serbian state until the late 14th century. It was held by magnates [[Nikola Altomanovi\u0107]] until 1373, then [[\u0110ura\u0111 I Bal\u0161i\u0107]] until 1377, after which it was taken by [[Tvrtko I of Bosnia]], during the [[Fall of the Serbian Empire]].\n\nBosnian magnate [[Sandalj Hrani\u0107]] received southern Konavle and its city Sokol in 1392,{{sfn|Vego|1957|p=72}} and also held Vrsinje (as mentioned in 1424).<ref name=\"umetnosti1940\">{{cite book|author=Srpska akademija nauka i umetnosti|title=Glas|issue=182|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zt8rAQAAIAAJ|year=1940|publisher=U Kralj.-srpskoj dr\u017eavnoj \u0161tampariji|page=165|quote=<!--\u0412\u0440\u0441\u0438\u045a\u0435 \u0458\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u043f\u0430\u0434\u0430\u043b\u043e \u0421\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0430\u0459\u0443-->}}</ref> In the 1440s, there were frequent flights from Trebinje, Vrsinje and Dra\u010devica into Ragusan territory.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Niko Kapetani\u0107|author2=Nenad Vekari\u0107|title=Stanovni\u0161tvo Konavala|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HN3kAAAAIAAJ|date=1 January 1999|publisher=Zavod za povijesne znanosti HAZU|page=98}}</ref> After Bosnian king [[Thomas of Bosnia|Stephen Thomas]] and the Serbian despot reconciled,{{when|date=May 2016}} the [[Republic of Ragusa]] proposed a league against the \"Duke of St. Sava\", [[Stjepan Vuk\u010di\u0107 Kosa\u010da]].{{sfn|Bo\u017ei\u0107|1952|p=119}} In 1451, King Stephen Thomas ceded over the counties of Vrsinje and [[Dra\u010devica (\u017eupa)|Dra\u010devica]] to Ragusa.{{sfn|\u0106irkovi\u0107|Mihalj\u010di\u0107|1999|p=32}} The Ragusans were allowed to raise castles in the ceded territory.{{sfn|\u0106irkovi\u0107|Mihalj\u010di\u0107|1999|p=32}} Thomas' charter from 18 December 1451 also included the obligation that he would attack Stjepan Vuk\u010di\u0107 Kosa\u010da, but the ceding was only theoretical, as Duke Stjepan firmly held those territories.{{sfn|Bo\u017ei\u0107|1952|p=120}}\n\nDuring the period of the [[Duchy of St. Sava]], Vrsinje changed hands several times from the Duchy to the Ottomans, and from the Ottomans back to the Duchy.{{sfn|Atanasovski|1979|p=117}} Vrsinje was held by the Ottomans already in September 1465.{{sfn|Atanasovski|1979|p=117}} Ottoman ''[[suba\u015fi]]'' are present in Vrsinje on 17 April and 20 August 1466, while [[Vlachs (social class)|Vlachs shepherd community]] of Zupci, as ''jurisdictio Turcorum'', are present there on 7 October 1466.{{sfn|Atanasovski|1979|p=117}} As seen from the Ottoman ''[[defter]]'' of 1475\u201377, the Zupci ''nahija'' replaced Vrsinje.{{sfn|Atanasovski|1979|p=118}} The Zupci had earlier been mentioned as a family or people part of Vrsinje; in 1403 as \"homo de Versigna Xube\u00e7\", in 1421 as \"de Versigne de genere Zuba\u00e7\", in 1466 as \"de Versigne Vlachos Xubci sic dictos\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Archiv f\u00fcr slavische Philologie|volume=19|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J1fRAAAAMAAJ|year=1897|publisher=Europa Printing|page=26}}</ref> The tribe of Zupci replaced the name of Vrsinje.{{sfn|Duni\u0107|1967|p=76}} On 28 January 1501, a new ''vojvoda'' of Novi, Vrsinje and Trebinje is mentioned;<ref name=\"Hercegovine1955\">{{cite book|author=Istorisko dru\u0161tvo Bosne i Hercegovine|volume=7|title=Godi\u0161njak|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6k0iAAAAMAAJ|year=1955|pages=57, 64}}</ref> this is the last time Vrsinje is mentioned as an administrative unit.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Atanasovski|first=Veljan|title=Pad Hercegovine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j4whAAAAMAAJ|year=1979|publisher=Istorijski Institut|pages=13, 47, 71, 117, 118|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bo\u017ei\u0107|first=Ivan|title=\u0414\u0443\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0438\u043a \u0438 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0443 XIV \u0438 XV \u0432\u0435\u043a\u0443|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7n1TAAAAYAAJ|year=1952|publisher=\u041d\u0430\u0443\u0447\u043d\u0430 \u043a\u045a\u0438\u0433\u0430|pages=119, 120, 190, 207|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=\u0106irkovi\u0107|first1=Sima|authorlink1=Sima \u0106irkovi\u0107|last2=Mihalj\u010di\u0107|first2=Rade|authorlink2=Rade Mihalj\u010di\u0107|script-title=sr:\u041b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043d \u0441\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433 \u0441\u0440\u0435\u0434\u045a\u0435\u0433 \u0432\u0435\u043a\u0430|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AypYAAAAMAAJ|year=1999|publisher=Knowledge|ref=harv|language=sr}}\n* {{cite book|last=Duni\u0107|first=Mihailo|title=Les Familles nobles de Hum et de Trebinje ...|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6Y8OAQAAIAAJ|year=1967|publisher=Acad\u00e9mie serbe des sciences et des arts|pages=53, 76, 77|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Jire\u010dek|first=Josif Konstantin|title=Trgova\u010dki drumovi i rudnici Srbije i Bosne u srednjem vijeku|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BB89AAAAMAAJ|year=1951|publisher=Svjetlost|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Kurtovi\u0107|first=Esad|title=\u0420\u0430\u0434\u043e\u0441\u0430\u043b\u0438\u045b\u0438 - \u043f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u0458\u0435\u0440 \"\u0458\u0435\u0434\u043d\u043e\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0430\" \u0441\u0440\u0435\u0434\u045a\u0435\u0433\u0430 \u0432\u0438\u0458\u0435\u043a\u0430|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MSsqCwAAQBAJ|year=2009|publisher=Istorijski institut Beograd|pages=23 |id=GGKEY:WUKYQDYP46L|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Peco|first=Asim|title=Iz jezi\u010dke teorije i prakse|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lc0cAAAAMAAJ|year=1987|publisher=Nau\u010dna knj.|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Rudi\u0107|first=Srdjan|title=\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0430 \u0418\u043b\u0438\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433 \u0433\u0440\u0431\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430: The Nobility of the Illyric Coat of Arms|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FHB6BwAAQBAJ&pg=PA107|year=2006|publisher=Istorijski institut Beograd|isbn=978-86-7743-055-9|page=107|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|author=SKA|title=Spomenik Srpske kraljevske akademije|volume=62\u201367|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Dl-1qjyPwxUC|year=1925|publisher=U Dr\u017eavnoj \u0161tampariji Kraljevne Srbije|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Vego|first=Marko|title=Naselja bosanske srednjevjekovne dr\u017eave|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yoPRAAAAMAAJ|year=1957|publisher=Svjetlost|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Dobra\u0161inovi\u0107i iz Vrsinja (Datiranje natpisa na ste\u0107ku Vuka\u0161ina Dobra\u0161inovi\u0107a iz Konjskog kod Trebinja), Godi\u0161njak CBI 39, Sarajevo 2010, 163-171.\n\n{{coord|42.6400204|18.3921432|region:BA_type:adm2nd|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vrsinje}}\n[[Category:Medieval Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Historical regions of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n", "name_user": "Amkgp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFurther reading:clean up,typo(s) fixed: 163-171 \u2192 163\u2013171", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vrsinje"}
